View this post on Instagram

Fatteh is the perfect lockdown food. Originating during WW1 in the Levant, it was a way of using whatever leftovers people had in the house when fresh food was hard to come by. It is a layered dish with bits of cut bread at the bottom covered with a stewed vegetable or meat and topped with a garlicky yoghurt tahini sauce. To elevate it a notch further, finish off with sizzling butter or ghee fried nuts, some chopped fresh parsley and of course some pomegranate seeds! If you want to find out more join us this Friday at 3pm london time for a live how to. üë©üèª‚Äçüç≥* * * * * #catering #cateringservice #hongkong #myhkmoment #pomegranatekitchen #cooking #cookingathome #cheflife #buzzfeast #londoncaterer #londoncatering #londoneventplanner #hongkongfoodie #londonfoodies #healthyfood #fatteh #levant #syrianfood #lebanesefood #lockdownfood #leftoversforlunch #chickpeas #tahini #pittabread #brunchathome

A post shared by Pomegranate Kitchen (@pomkitch) on May 6, 2020 at 4:16am PDT

With some bread, leftover stewed veggies or meat, tahini sauce, and yogurt you can make this super-easy and filling dish. During WWI, when food was difficult to buy, people got creative and created fatteh. Find this recipe by @pomkitch.

Spiced chickpeas, spinach, avocado, juicy cherry tomatoes and lemon tahini dressing. After all the sunshine of the past few weeks I think the rain is quite welcoming. Certainly good for the seedlings in the vegetable patch. It‚Äôs amazing how everything looks so much greener now. We made falafel on Saturday. I saved some cooked chickpeas to either make humus with or pop into a salad. Well salad took my fancy today. I popped the cooked chickpeas in a pan with a little olive oil, cumin and cayenne to warm through and absorb the spices and then add a little sprinkling of white wine vinegar. I always have spinach in my fridge, I really like it as a salad leaf, add tomatoes and avocado and a tahini dressing. Put a tablespoon of tahini in a bowl and add the juice of half a lemon and stir. It will thicken significantly so add a tablespoon of boiling water and stir to a thin pouring consistency. Season and drizzle over the salad.

A post shared by ëÅç Nordic Kitchen stories ëÅç (@nordickitchenstories) on Apr 28, 2020 at 4:21am PDT
